In this notebook, we describe our solution, from the extraction of relevant features to the generation of explanations and model insights. Our efforts were devoted to three stages of the interpretability in Machine Learning, defined by Kim and Finale in [1]:

  • Pre-model: through the generation of high-level features with relevant semantics.
  • In-model: by choosing models that are well-established as interpretable models (e.g., Decision Trees, Scorecards, etc.), by promoting sparcity, and by using monotonic constraints to ensure consistency between the learnt patterns and the domain priors.
  • Post-model: by simplifying models and studying hidden layers of Deep Neural Networks.

In the next sections, we will explain in details each one of these steps.

Pre-model Intepretability (Additional features and Corrections)¶

After doing some Exploratory Data Analysis (not included in this notebook), we designed additional features.

Observation: All the monotonic decreasing features were corrected to be increasing with respect to the probability of being rejected. Thus, the results on global explanations presented below consider the complement value of the feature $(MAX(X_{ft}) - X_{ft})$ instead of the original one $(X_{ft})$ for monotonic decreasing features.

Feature Engineering: Mising values per type¶

Since mising information may be considered as a risk factor in the assignment of credit, we built a set of additional features describing the mising value state (-7, -8, -9) of each feature before applying imputation. As can be observed in the table below, these features are good indicators of rejection.

Feature Engineering: Global rank-based features¶

The relative position in the population (i.e., percentile) of the client on the set of features is a good overall indicator of the client's risk. Therefore, we computed the rank of the client (monotonically increasing on the probability of bad) on each feature. Then, we computed global features such as the mean, median, maximum, minimum, 25-th percentile, 75-th percentile of the client's rank.

The plots below show that using each one of these features alone leads to a high predictive performance, up to a ROC AUC of 0.77.

Feature Engineering: Pairwise Interactions¶

Most interpretable models (e.g., Decision Trees, Logistic Regression, Scorecards) do not consider the interaction between features. Thus, we extracted features that account for pairwise interactions between monotonic features. Namely:

  • The relative ordering of features (i.e., $rank(A) < rank(B)$, $rank(A) > rank(B)$)
  • The minimum and maximum of the relative values (e.g., $min(rank(A), rank(B)$)
  • Arithmetic aggregation of the relative values (i.e., addition and product of features).

We chose these operators since they preserve monotonocity and can be easily replicated by a human expert. Below, we show the predicitve performance of these features.

In-model Interpretability¶

Our final solution consists of an ensemble of three models with different degrees of interpretability.

  • Scorecard.
  • Random Forest.
  • Deep Neural Network.

We follow our previously proposed framework for the objective analysis of interpretability that consists on studying the "3 Cs of interpretability": correctness, completeness and compactness. Further details about our work, can be found in [2]

We decompose the analysis of the in-model interpretability on three blocks, depending on the type of model we use.

Scorecards¶

  • Binning: while typical strategies to bin features consist of equal-frequency and equal-width which do not take into account the supervised labels, we used the decision thresholds of a Decision Tree to decide the bins. We limited the number of bins to 20.

  • Sparsity: we used differential-coding [3] for the binning and $L_1$ regularization to ensure a sparse number of scores.

  • Monotonicity: we added a non-negative constraint to the scores associated to monotonic features. Since we are using differential-coding [3], adding this constraint to the scores ensures monotonicity.

In the image below, we show the most important features ordered by average impact. Reddish colors contribute to rejection whereas blueish contribute to acceptance. The colorbar was scaled to the percentile of the value in the feature domain.

As can be seen in the image, the weights follow the monotonic constraints and, in most cases, the number of bins (different colors) per features is small (3-6 in most cases), leading to a simple model.

ft_impact = []
global_ft_weight = model.output_layer.get_weights()[0].ravel()

for i, f in enumerate(model.all_features):
    fweight = model.all_bin_scores[i].get_weights()[0].ravel()
    fweight = fweight.copy()

    df_expected_value = np.asarray(model.apply_binning(df, f))
    df_expected_value = (df_expected_value * fweight[np.newaxis]).sum(axis=1)
    df_expected_value = df_expected_value.mean()
    
    next_impact = abs(df_expected_value * global_ft_weight[i])
    
    ft_impact.append((-next_impact, f, i))

heatmap = np.zeros((len(model.all_features), 100))

ft_impact = sorted(ft_impact)

valid = []
for idx_, (imp, f, i) in enumerate(ft_impact):
    fweight = model.all_bin_scores[i].get_weights()[0].ravel()
    orig_weights = fweight.copy()
    
    fweight = np.cumsum(fweight)
    fweight = [fweight[0]] + list(fweight)
    binning, _ = zip(*model.binning[f])
    
    binning = list(binning) + [df[f].max()]
    binning[0] = df[f].min()
    
    df_expected_value = np.asarray(model.apply_binning(df, f))
    df_expected_value = (df_expected_value * orig_weights[np.newaxis]).sum(axis=1)
    df_expected_value = df_expected_value.mean()

    values = df[f].values.astype(np.float)
    progress = np.linspace(0, 1, 100)
    progress = values.min() + progress * (values.max() - values.min())
    score = np.asarray([global_ft_weight[i] * np.asarray(fweight)[np.asarray(binning) <= p][-1] for p in progress])
    
    heatmap[idx_] = score
    valid.append(np.abs(score).max() > 1e-3)

ticks = [f[1] for f, v in zip(ft_impact, valid) if v]

N = 5
rpt = np.repeat(np.arange(len(ticks)), N)
img_ = heatmap[rpt]
valid_ = np.asarray(valid)[rpt]
ticks = [ticks[i // N].replace(',', ',\n') if i % N == N // 2 else '' for i in range(len(img_))]

M = 30 * N

ax = plt.figure(figsize=(20, 20))
im = plt.imshow(img_[valid_][: M], cmap='jet')
plt.yticks(np.arange(len(ticks))[: M], ticks[: M])
plt.colorbar(im)
plt.show()

Random Forest¶

Although Random Forests are not considered interpretable models in general, individual trees within the ensemble are interpretable (given a limited depth). Therefore, we can train a large ensemble and pick the explanation from those estimators that agree with the overall decision.

The final explanation is chosen from the path from the source to the tree leaf with highest correctness (i.e., purity). This criterion follows the previously proposed framework (i.e., the 3 Cs of interpretability), considering completeness and compactness as fixed given limited-size trees. We limited the depth of the individual estimators to 4, being a good tradeoff between predictive performance and model interpretability.

This framework allows to generate diverse and complementary explanations without compromising the interpretability of a single decision tree.

Below, we show an illustrative example of a tree trained without the intrinsic randomness of a Random Forest.

Nearest Neighbors by Deep Neural Networks¶

Humans are prone to explain by comparison. Thus, case-based reasoning is a traditional way of explaining decisions. However, choosing the right distance may be crucial on finding relevant examples. Namely, Euclidean and Manhattan distances may be suboptimal on finding good candidates for comparison.

In this sense, while Deep Neural Networks are considered as blackbox models in general, they are capable of learning semantic representations that preserve relevant properties in terms of sample similarity as has been observed in word and visual embeddings.

We extract two types of explanations from DNN:

  • Similar: the most similar example in the latent space from the same class.
  • Opponent: the most similar example in the latent space from the opposite class.

Moreover, in order to facilitate the comparison, we include a sensitivity analysis of which features make them similar or different, respectively.

The architecture of our Deep Neural Network has two streams. One stream without constraints for non-monotonic features and one stream with non-negative constraints for monotonic feautes. Finally, both streams are merged (with further monotonic layers) to produce the final latent space. The following figure illustrates the architecture:

As the plots below demonstrate, the embeddings obtained by the DNN are able to organize the clients according to their probability of rejection, contrarily to the distribution observed in the original feature space and in the extended space after feature engineering.

from mpl_toolkits import mplot3d

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))

mask_orig = np.ones(emb_orig.shape[0], dtype=np.bool)
mask_ft_eng = np.ones(emb_ft_eng.shape[0], dtype=np.bool)
for ch in range(emb_orig.shape[1]):
    mask_orig = mask_orig & (emb_orig[:, ch] >= np.percentile(emb_orig[:, ch], 10))
    mask_orig = mask_orig & (emb_orig[:, ch] <= np.percentile(emb_orig[:, ch], 90))
    
    mask_ft_eng = mask_ft_eng & (emb_ft_eng[:, ch] >= np.percentile(emb_ft_eng[:, ch], 5))
    mask_ft_eng = mask_ft_eng & (emb_ft_eng[:, ch] <= np.percentile(emb_ft_eng[:, ch], 95))

plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
plt.scatter(emb_orig[mask_orig, 0], emb_orig[mask_orig, 1], c=y[e_index][mask_orig], alpha=0.2)
plt.title('Original features')

plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
plt.scatter(emb_ft_eng[mask_ft_eng, 0], emb_orig[mask_ft_eng, 1], c=y[e_index][mask_ft_eng], alpha=0.2)
plt.title('Extended features')

Post-model Intepretability¶

To improve the completeness (replicability) and simplicity of the explanations we simplified the models a posteriori.

  • Decision Trees: pruning of branches that did not lead to further class refinement.
  • Scorecards: building rules by merging neighboring bins that are monotonic on the decision for a given lcoal sample.

Conclusions¶

As part of this work, we addressed the three main forms of interpretability in Machine Learning (pre, in, and post-model) [2].

We covered all the major trends in interpretability, from white-box models with regularization, to monotonic constraints, to sensitivity analysis.

The core idea of the proposed solution is to satisfy the curiosity of decision makers by providing complentary explanations such as the ones obtained from an ensemble of trees, a scorecard, and similar/opponent examples. An explanation is valuable as long as it is able to convince the audience, being a core property, the expansion and diversity of the types of insights the model can provide.
